<title type="html"><![CDATA[Re: Uhh... the NES CPU clock]]></title>

<content type="html" xml:base="http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=1675&amp;p=14347#p14347"><![CDATA[
<div class="quotetitle">Fx3 wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent"><br />By the way, I mean the number 1786840. If you consider the even/odd frames cycle subtraction, would you get 1789772.7272727?<br /></div><br />523 lines each of 341 cycles and 1 line of 340 cycles = 178683 PPU cycles per 2 fields, or 10720980 PPU cycles per 2 fields, or 5360490 PPU cycles per 60 fields, or 1786830 CPU cycles per 60 fields. One could call a mode that uses this CPU frequency "Exact 60 Hz" with long description: "Underclocks the NES CPU by 0.16% to make the output frame rate match the common 60.00 Hz frame rate of PC displays."<br /><br /><div class="quotetitle"><b>Quote:</b></div><div class="quotecontent"><br /><div class="quotetitle">blargg wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">I found that 1789772.7272... = 1789772 + 8/11.<br /></div><br />Uhh... you mean 0.7272... into a fraction? Something like 72/99 -&gt; 8/11? <img src="http://forums.nesdev.com/images/smilies/icon_wink.gif" alt=";)" title="Wink" /></div><br />Yes, 11 will appear in the denominator.<br /><br />In fact, the NTSC color burst frequency is <em>defined</em> as 455/2 cycles per line times 525/2 lines per field times 60000/1001 fields per second = 14332500000/4004 cycles per second = 39375000/11 = 3579545.4&#773;5&#773; cycles per second. The true NTSC NES CPU frequency is defined as exactly half this: 19687500/11 = 1789772.7&#773;2&#773; cycles per second. But for use on a PC, you probably want to underclock.<p>Statistics: Posted by <a href="http://forums.nesdev.com/memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&amp;u=9">tepples</a> — Wed Jun 21, 2006 4:04 pm</p><hr />
]]></content>
